body:
### Issue

I've been working on an advent of code solver using specialization to evaluate the separate parts of the challenge if they have been implemented. I found my code stopped compiling on nightly after September 9th 2022.

### Code Reproduction

I've tried to create a minimal reproduction case.

Cargo.toml
```rust
[package]
name = "regression"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
is_type = "0.2"
```

src/main.rs
```rust
#![feature(specialization)]
#![feature(adt_const_params)]
#![allow(incomplete_features)]

#[derive(PartialEq, Eq)]
pub enum Enum {
    Foo,
    Bar,
}

pub trait Run<'a, const PART: Enum> {
    type Output;

    fn run(&'a self) -> Self::Output;
}

pub trait Test<'a, T> {
    fn test(&'a self, expected: T);
}

impl<'a, T, U> Test<'a, U> for T
where
    T: Run<'a, { Enum::Foo }, Output = U>,
    U: is_type::Is<Type = T::Output>,
{
    fn test(&'a self, expected: U) {}
}

fn main() {}
```

However, the following replacement of Enum with u32 compiles.
```rust
#![feature(specialization)]
#![feature(adt_const_params)]
#![allow(incomplete_features)]

pub trait Run<'a, const PART: u32> {
    type Output;

    fn run(&'a self) -> Self::Output;
}

pub trait Test<'a, T> {
    fn test(&'a self, expected: T);
}

impl<'a, T, U> Test<'a, U> for T
where
    T: Run<'a, 0, Output = U>,
    U: is_type::Is<Type = T::Output>,
{
    fn test(&'a self, _expected: U) {}
}

fn main() {}
```

Should this not compile? Why is a const enum different from a u32?

### Bisect
@lcnr since they might have an idea how this changeset could affect things.

Bisected to nightly-2022-09-09 with commit ccb5595df2ed412eda6444edc7eaf06f709fa79d for issue with ```bash cargo-bisect-rustc --start=2022-06-01```.
